{{Infobox language |name=Samburu |nativename=Sampur, ɔl Maa |states=[[Kenya]] |region=Samburu district of [[Rift Valley Province]] |speakers={{sigfig|237,000|2}} |date=2009 census |ref=e18 |speakers2= (including Camus) |familycolor=Nilo-Saharan |fam2=[[Eastern Sudanic languages|Eastern Saharan]] |fam3=[[Eastern Nilotic languages|Eastern Nilotic]] |fam4=Lotuxo–Teso |fam5=Lotuxo–Maa |fam6=[[Maa languages|Maa]] |iso3=saq |glotto=samb1315 |glottorefname=Samburu |dia1=Camus }}
'''Samburu''' is a [[Maa languages|Maa language]] dialect spoken by [[Samburu people|Samburu]] pastoralists in northern [[Kenya]]. The Samburu number about 128,000 (or 147,000 including the Camus/Chamus).{{when|date=April 2012}} The Samburu dialect is closely related to [[Camus dialect]] (88% to 94% lexical similarity) and to the South Maasai dialects (77% to 89% lexical similarity). The word "Samburu" itself may derive from the Maa word ''saamburr'' for a leather bag the Samburu use.
